<br>
But he was held still in an invisible, vicelike grip as the spell took hold of Kyonae, making her pallid complexion glow.  Rather than dying or doing something horrid that poor Menion expected, her eyes fluttered and she breathed a sigh of relief, the trembling in her joints lessening, though not stopping, as the spell was not that great.  When the glow finally faded, Menion was able to move and he quickly reached to feel her lifebeat, and was surprised to find it beating swiftly beneath his fingers.  Her eyes were closed and her expression took on the face of one who has been lulled into a peaceful dream.<br>
<br>
He looked up at Mirak, guilt tugging down at the corners of his lips, but said nothing.  He nodded briefly in thanks and shifted Kyonae's almost non existing weight in his arms, and pulled her closer, walking off to talk to Cedric.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do not mind him,&quot; Naomi purred, walking up from behind Mirak with an all knowing expression.  She leaned on the staff she bore and coughed into her hand.  &quot;He cares for her, Menion.  More than anyone else has cared, I'll wager.&quot;  She wiped her lips with a handkerchief, and stuffed the rag back into her robe pocket.  &quot;She is strong enough to travel now.  How ironic, it is...that the most powerful of souls are always trapped in the weakest mortal shells.&quot; <br>
